example.p:
Use elimination to solve the system of equations.

\begin{alignedat}{9}
3a \amp {}+{} \amp 2b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp -1\amp\hphantom{blankblank} \amp(1)\\
a \amp {}-{} \amp 2b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp -3\amp\amp(2) \\
2a \amp {}+{} \amp 3b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 4\amp\amp(3) 
\end{alignedat}

solution.p:
Substitute the coordinates of each of the three points into the equation of the parabola to obtain three equations:
\begin{alignedat}{9} \alert{3} =\amp a(\alert{1})^2{}+{} \amp b(\alert{1}) \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp \\ \alert{5} =\amp a(\alert{3})^2{}+{} \amp b(\alert{3}) \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp \\ \alert{9} =\amp a(\alert{4})^2{}+{} \amp b(\alert{4}) \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp \end{alignedat}
or, equivalently,
\begin{alignedat}{9} a \amp {}+{} \amp b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 3\amp\hphantom{blankblank} \amp(1)\\ 9a \amp {}+{} \amp 3b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 5\amp\amp(2) \\ 16a \amp {}+{} \amp 4b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 9\amp\amp(3) \end{alignedat}
This is a system of three equations in the three unknowns a, b, and c. To solve the system, we first eliminate c. Add -1 times Equation (1) to Equation (2) to obtain 8a + 2b = 2 \hphantom{blankblank}(4) and add -1 times Equation (1) to Equation (3) to get
15a + 3b = 6 \hphantom{blankblank}(5)
We now have a system of two linear equations in two variables:
\begin{alignedat}{9} 8a \amp {}+{} \amp 2b \amp {}={} \amp 2\amp\hphantom{blankblank}\amp(4) \\ 15a \amp {}+{} \amp 3b \amp {}={} \amp 6\amp\amp(5) \end{alignedat}
We eliminate b from Equations (4) and (5): Add -3 times Equation (4) to 2 times Equation (5) to get


\begin{alignedat}{9}
2500a \amp {}+{} \amp 50b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 6.20\amp\hphantom{blankblank} \amp(1)\\
3600a \amp {}+{} \amp 60b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 7.8\amp\amp(2) \\
4900a \amp {}+{} \amp 70b \amp {}+{} \amp c \amp {}={} \amp 10.6\amp\amp(3) 
\end{alignedat}

Eliminating c from Equations (1) and (2) yields Equation (4), and eliminating c from Equations (2) and (3) yields Equation (5).

\begin{alignedat}{9}
1100a \amp {}+{} \amp 10b  \amp {}={} \amp 1.60\amp\hphantom{blankblank}\amp(4) \\
1300a \amp {}+{} \amp 10b  \amp {}={} \amp 2.8\amp\amp(5) 
\end{alignedat}

Eliminating b from Equations (4) and (5) gives us

	\begin{aligned}
	200a \amp= 1.20\\
	a \amp= 0.006
	\end{aligned}

li.p:
If Andre's feet are at the origin, then the vertex of the ball's trajectory is the point (10, 11), and its y-intercept is (0, 7). Start with the vertex form for a parabola:

				\begin{aligned}
				y \amp = a(x - x_v)^2 + y_v\\
				y \amp= a(x - 10)^2 + 11
				\end{aligned}

			We still need to know the value of a. We can substitute the coordinates of any point on the parabola for x and y and solve for a. We will use the point (0, 7):

				\begin{aligned}
				7 \amp= a(0 - 10)^2 + 11\\
				7 \amp= 100a + 11\\
				a \amp= -0.04
				\end{aligned}

			The equation of the trajectory is y = -0.04(x - 10)^2 + 11.

We would like to know if the point (15, 10) is on the trajectory of Andre's free-throw. Substitute x = 15 into the equation:

				\begin{aligned}
				y \amp= -0.04(15 - 10)^2 + 11\\
				\amp= -0.04(25) + 11 = 10
				\end{aligned}

			Andre's shot will score.
